messages.content: Oh, god. I don't feel great about this. The world made a lot more sense when it was just me and her, out against the world. Now we have a hundred people, all so sure of what they're here to do and what they have to say to everyone else. Why did she have to let down those ladders? Why did she do this to me?
I know I shouldn't blame her. She was just doing what she thought was right. But, a little hesitation... it goes a long way, doesn't it? Isn't that what's said?
And I still don't even know what to call her.
"Well, well... Hey there." 58 gives a slight wave with a smug expression.
"Took you long enough."
"I was offering the lady a lead."
"Excuse me, sir, but...why do you look like that?" To 58.
"How should I know? I’m an amnesiac, same as you all."
"W-Well... Have you *seen* yourself?"
“Look like what.”
“You’re the one who’s white. That’s more odd, really.”
"I’ve seen reactions to it." He looks at 56.
"Are you really not seeing...this?" I gesture to 58.
"Hey, it's okay! I'm not the prettiest fella in the cell block either, haha."
I just squint at him.
"No, don't say that!" I put my hand on John's shoulder. "You're perfectly beautiful, dear."
“This is stupid. Why are we talking about this?”
"Well, since we are all here, we can check out the door, can't we? It's a very difficult to open looking door, and I wanna open it."
I do not mention my mirror. I'm not letting anyone touch it.
“Sure.” I walk over and open the door.
"Ah... but you said I was scary. Can I be scary, beautiful and small all at the same time? That sounds like an awful lot to juggle."
"The door, yeah... Seems pretty ominous to me." 58.
"You're still not small, John." I mutter.
"Hm? Did you say something?" I look towards... Fours? Is that what they're calling them?
I go to open the door with The Unnamed Person Who Has The Number 63.

I trail behind the one who opened the door, uncharacteristically quiet as I do. I can’t help it. There are a lot of people here, which is - overwhelming. It’s overwhelming. *Not* scary, I’m not *scared,* I’m just *overwhelmed.*
There’s no need for anyone to go over to open the door, because I’m the one opening it, and surely have already done so by now.
I don't care about the door.
But if they want to go through the door after it’s opened, that makes sense.

"I just..." I sigh. "I don't understand why you're so committed to trying to convince us all that you're so utterly unintimidating. It feels... manipulative, right? We can all see you. You are large, and threatening, and I don't think some waffling around about your 'inner size' is going to be enough to fool most people about your capabilities. Regardless of your intent! I know that's not what you want to hear, but it's true... right, guys?"
I look around inquisitively.
"What's your problem? Doesn't that seem discriminatory?"

It does not open. Instead, a voice comes from it. "You have reached the door of death. The end of what made you you, forever, hidden at the end of the labyrinth. You are not tainted by any other door yet today. Your requirement, Inmate #63, is-" 

"Not yet fulfilled." A floating woman appears in the center of the room, interrupting the door.
“Kyahaha, so desperate for our approval, hyah..” I mumble under my breath with disdain.
Whoa, what the fuck?
I try harder to open the door. I wasn’t really giving it my all before.
Oh, of course. My arch nemesis. The floating woman.

"M- manipulating?!"

Oh, oh dear. Oh dear. They're actually right, I think. Not about the manipulation part, but what's the point of... hold that thought, who might this be?
"Where are your eyes?"

I'm taken aback. "What kind of prejudice do you think I could have built up against this guy that I've never met before? I mean, I even know his name! I'm not sure I can say that for you! Surely I would be unfairly prejudiced against somebody else, right? I feel like... I'm being pretty objective, here."
Cute.

The door does not budge at all. It is unresponsive now. 

"I am your goddess, Ismalisa. The Goddess of Justice and Retribution. Welcome, you 7 sinners... to Sinspace." The floating woman gives a dismissive hand gesture to the door, which begins to sink into the ground. "Your atonement."
I flinch, confused and more than a little scared now. “W-what? Atoning for what? I didn’t do anything! Don’t lump me in with these f-f-freaks.”
“I don’t feel bad at all!” I kick the wall where the door used to be.

"Atonement? D- did we sin? No, no, no, that can't be right... I'm too small to sin... but at the same time, I suppose it's also valid to disagree with that, so maybe you're right...? Oh me, oh my... uuaah..."
"We shouldn't be blindly believing what this...creature is saying."
“Ugh, shut up, super-ugly! You’re a big hulking beast! Stop pretending like you’re not!”

So that's the challenge. 

Can I escape The Goddess' Prison without dying? Let's find out.

I look towards the goddess and say "What? I'm no sinner. Maybe you're the awful person for making me out to be the bad guy when I've been put into jail and trapped under rubble for no reason. If I did anything bad, I would remember it."

"I have robbed you all of your selves as punishment. You may not remember your crimes but their existence is undeniable. You will remain in Sinspace until you have atoned for your crimes against me. Only once you understand your crimes and atone for them will you be allowed to leave." Ismalisa.
“Quit ganging up on Mr. Beast.” I don’t remember his name. “He’s already admitted to being too timid to fight any of us.”
"I- I'm not pretending to be anything, I just... I'unno, I just am!"
"I'm really, really sorry!"
"Oh, ok. That makes sense." I look around. Is there any way to atone for my sins around here?
"You're still not small."
"Your apology means nothing, subhuman beast. You do not know what you have done." Ismalisa.
“Stop being racist, Ishmael.”
"Have you considered that maybe the reason why you were able to commit your crime in the first place is because you were so unwilling to believe yourself capable of it?"
"Can you prove to us that you aren't just making this stuff up?" To the guy without eyes.
I finally turn away from the door. It seems likely I’ll need to wait a bit to open it, because right now it isn’t here.
"I have no need to. If you are all insistent on never atoning you will simply be left here with the others and never regain yourselves or see the world ever again."

Ah. Well, that doesn't feel good at all. I suppose I can deduce that my sin wasn't littering, at least.

"I mean, that could be possible. I can't entirely discount it. Would it make you feel better if I called myself big instead, maybe? Would that ease the tension?"
"Yes, I would feel good about the truth. I... think I do, generally."
"It feels important to me."

"Well, okay. I guess all we have left to do is to solve the mystery, then!" I look towards everyone and clap my hands, (poorly) attempting to gain control of the conversation. "This is going to be fun, right?"
I look up at him. "Big might be too small of a word, though... how about 'huge'?"
“Are you actually here, or is this one of those dumb tricks?” I swat a hand at the floating woman.
"W-... well, okay! I am a huge, beastly sinner, then." I smile, hopefully in a way that comes off amiable enough. Did I ever get the chance to floss? Oh dear.
I frown slightly less at him, I guess.

"How are we supposed to atone for crimes we can't remember? Your story makes no sense, Goddess." 58 leans back against a wall smugly.

"The doors." Ismalisa is touched by 63. She doesn't seem to care.

...you know what? Maybe this is reverse psychology.

I walk into the wall where the door was. Maybe it's like a painting that lets you in if you jump into it.
I drag her down to earth.
The door was not attached to a wall. It did not lead to anything and was just in the middle of the garden.
Oh, well alright.
I walk through the space it was on multiple times, I mean.

I scowl. “Bitch, you’ve got to be joking if you think I’m just gonna hold hands with you all for mystery-solving-funtimes. This entire thing is a stupid prank, or something. Yeah.” I say this with more confidence than is even remotely deserved.
She is not moved by this in the slightest.

Is she immobile?

I attempt to climb her.
"Whaaat? Staying positive should only help us, right? We need to stick together, and become friends! Well, you're *already* my friends, but you know..." To 56.
"Could you tell me what crime I committed so I might begin making up for it, please? What if I said I was sorry?"
"Don't be sorry in advance, John. It's unbecoming."
"What if you really did just litter?"
"What if you did nothing at all, in fact? We have no proof of these crimes, except the words of somebody who is also, conveniently, locked in this 'sinspace' with us."

"Well, um. I'd still be very sorry about that..."

My brain feels fuzzy.
"Surely, she must have committed the greatest sin of all. Look at what she is capable of!"
"She could have done anything!!"
“None of you are my friends!” I say. “You’re all criminals, a-and sinners, right?”

"Sinspace contains 6 doors representing your journey on this mortal coil. Birth, Growth, Corruption, Sin, Retribution, and Death.  A maximum of 1 door per day may be entered per person. You did not progress through each of these stages of your lives in the same order as each other. Everything you need is contained within your 6 doors." Ismalisa is not climbed because 63 cannot seem to get a solid grip.
"Personally, I don't believe that. We have zero proof of it being true, after all! That's rule one of the mystery: if there's no proof, it isn't true!" To 56.
“Any of you could be a comrade or enemy.  It doesn’t matter quite yet.”

...

I think it would be nice if we could all be friends...
“Also, we all went through birth first, so you’re wrong.”
I nod. "Death last, too, hopefully."
"I shall be watching. Goodbye." With a wave of her hand, a door rises in the place where the Death door used to be. It's a single plain looking door marked Sin.
"W... would that imply entering the Death door would have us killed...?"

One door per day per perso- That's such a hard limit! How will I escape this prison the fastest if everyone goes before me?  I need to find the doors. Where are the-

Well, that works out.
"I'm going first."
"Wait, wait, you haven't explained anything! Why should we believe we did anything wrong? How can we atone for anything if we go about the whole thing believing we're good people?"
"This is all meaningless. Come on."
"You have to abide by the rules of the challenge if you want to beat it, Fours."
"You do not get a choice for the first door, 57." Ismalisa smirks cruelly. The door swings open and begins sucking everyone in with immense force.
"I-I guess, if that's how you want to look at it. But I just- why is this the person setting our challenge? I'd like to set a challenge... someday..."
"Awawawawawawaaa!!!!!!!"

That works out.

I jump into the door.
I jerk back and try to grab hold of something solid before getting dragged in.
I grab Ismal.
I end up grabbing the person trying to grab Ismalisa.
63's hand cannot grip Ismalisa. She remains outside.
What.
Bullshit.
“Gyahhh!” I screech, pinwheeling wildly through the air. “Fuck! Fuck you!”
"This will be so fun!"
My hands fail, and I fall through, silently.

I plant my feet firmly in the ground, digging my nails into the dirt! I need to stay strong! If someone needs to take hold of something, they can grab me! Then can... oh no, oh gosh. My arms are flailing everywhere. This is no good, Oh, no no no. This is horrific. I'd hurt someone. No, no, no...
https://tenor.com/view/bowser-speeeeen-spin-arms-super-paper-mario-spm-gif-17726892

Everyone is sent flying out of the door with the same force they entered. It vanishes immediately after. They’re no longer in the garden. Instead, they find themselves in some kind of desert/beach. Above them is a giant red semi-transparent dome that seems to stretch out far in every direction. On one end of the desert is the ocean, which ends at the dome. On the other end is a forest. There’s smoke rising from somewhere in this direction, about the size of a campfire. You can see another part of land beyond the forest that has curved further towards your right containing a mountain. You cannot access the mountain directly, however. Your only directions for now are the forest or the beach.

You’ll get to that as soon as you get out of the sand the force of the door has partially buried you under, at least. It’s not impossible for anyone to dig themselves out but it does feel immediately annoying.

"H-h-h-h..." I choke on my words, trying to process what just happened. Did I teleport? Did the door speak? Can all doors speak? Should I have been trying to get information out of them this whole time? I definitely went through a few doors. Maybe one of them could have helped me. Maybe one of them could have been somebody I trusted instead of this... this... accusatory bullshit!

I attempt to dig myself out.

"Hey, what the heck was that? Was that, like, a memory...? Did we all see the same thing?"
I get out of the sand. “Well, Jon’s dead.”
"Who is Jon? Do you mean John?"
“That’s what I said. Jon.” I point to Jon.
I wave. "Hello."
"Ohh... Their names are so similar. Why is he dead?"
“I killed him.”
"But, he's right there... Don't be silly."
“Or metaphorically did? Yeah, I dunno.”

I dig myself!! Out of the sand!!

"I'm alive, probably! I finally remember things! And, if I might say, my sin doesn't seem fair at all!"
"Shit." 58 spits sand out and tries to brush himself off as he gets up. "You guys actually got any info out of that? Mine was nonsense."
"I don't understand. Can someone describe what they saw, so I can understand if we all saw the same thing in the door?"
“It’s obvious we didn’t.”
"I got to watch myself be born!"
“That doesn’t seem like a sin.”
I retch a little and get my footing. "I-I mean, in his case, it might be."
"E- exactly! It's not fair! I even got the Goddess Ismalisa's blessing! Isn't that, you know- doesn't that sort of exempt you from sin?"
“No.”

"Oh, it was you? I don't remember seeing you. All I remember was me being better than some other guy who was weird."  I say to The Unnamed Person With The Number 63.

I look around the beach/desert. This just seems like Lots of trouble. I decide to stay here for a while before proceeding towards my next goal.

Still, me as... well, that? I must have been awesome, as I already knew.
I look around for 56. Where is that bundle of nerves?
I scowl and begin to wipe myself down. "That.. that was so stupid!!!!!!!! I mean, it clearly didn't, like..." I trail off, wringing my hands.
"Mine also seemed...birth related. I wonder if there's a pattern?"

"Look, John, whatever sin you've committed in the past, that's not the point right now. I just... you have to understand that Ismalisa has betrayed you, right? She's not the benevolent goddess you've been led to believe."
"Birth related?? Ewwwww...."
"I want you to be able to adapt to that fact."
“I don’t understand why I didn’t use a weapon.” I stare at my hands. “Maybe it was personal?”
"Please don't discriminate. Pregnancy and childbirth are normal things, and othering those who experience them only serves to increase societal tensions for everyone."
I try and move away as far from the killer as possible. "Augh. So are you saying the sin that you'e being 'punished' for is killing a dude???? What the hell's wrong with you, man!"
“I wasn’t pregnant.” I provide information on what I saw.

"Yes, I'm inclined to agree. This seems downright unfair to me! I mean, I'm some sort of Great Protector, apparently? That feels very pleasant. If I committed any sin more meaningful than existing, I'd love to make up for it."
"Apparently, I have multiple children. That's so cool! I can't wait to meet them!"
“Well, I can’t say. There wasn’t any context. But I don’t think it was entirely unwarranted.”

I scowl at the dumb white woman who I dislike. "N-normal things? Okay, whatever, but it's still an objectively fuckin' gross biological process." I wrinkle up my nose. "I mean, I can't believe that I would, uh..."
I try and divert my thoughts away from gross biological processes.
"Oh! Did you give birth in your memory, Ruthilla? Maybe we saw the same point in time."

"That's good. That's good. It's okay. We know you didn't mean to do anything wrong. You just... hitched your horse to the wrong wagon. We've all done it before." I walk over to John, and I wrap him in a tight embrace.
It's comforting.
Stop fucking hugging each other, you weird freaks!!!!!
"Oh, are you a fellow mother? Maybe we can bond over that? 😊" To 56.
I don't say this.
I hug this li'l Fours fellla back! Haha. How nice.
"No, not quite, John my dear." To John.
"The Goddess said my sin was pride. Though, is it truly pride if I've earned my place?" I scoff.

"G-gah!" I back away from the white woman. "I'm not a - Don't lump me in with you?? W-what, you think just because I'm the only other girl here that I'd engage in that sort of sicko shit??? I don't!!!!! I, um, uh..."
Realistic depiction of a panic attack.
“What?”

"I wasn’t pregnant either, as far as I know." 58 snickers. "All it said was that my sin was apathy. And… I think my name starts with L? I’ve got an inkling of that at least. Sounds like you all got way more info than me."

"You know, John, I think your hugeness is an advantage, honestly. The fact that you're so naturally inclined towards violence and fear just makes it mean even more when you manage to wrench yourself away from that. Really. It means a lot."
I release the hug.
I look towards 56. "Sixer, we should go find the next door together."
I make a frustrated noise, trying to dislodge myself from this mental spiral. "Well.. I guess out of all the total fuckin' losers and perverts here, you're the most tolerable. Probably."
"That's right." I nod.
“…I guess I should wait before deciding on killing him again, yeah. It could’ve been a mistake, or something I regret, or not real.” I’m a little out of it.

"I- yeah, that makes sense to me. Because I'm so massive and dangerous, I can leverage it in ways that only benefit my friends. Like a real Protector!" I find myself grinning. Ah, man, I'm really settling into my role, aren't I?
"Well, no, that's not what I meant."
"...Is it not?"

I scramble over to the side of Jon Fuckface, or whatever he was called. Sure, he's terrible, but everyone else here is also terrible. And, like, didn't that other guy say he had *killed* him? That's.. mildly concerning. Is what I would say if I cared.

"Leveraging being massive and dangerous is bad, John. Why would you want to be those things? Don't you believe in peace? I know it's hard for you... I know there's some part of you, deep down, that needs to be scary and murderous and whatever else. But we can fight it. Right?"
What is he talking about? Who cares?
"I... I don't know. Now that you're putting it like that, I'm not so sure of myself..."
I simply listen to this very interesting conversation!

"If I'm dead, then you're dead too. Since we're both here." 

I look around the beach. "Sixer, I think our best bet is over by that puff of smoke. I doubt staying in this beach for so long will help us."

It's peculiar how much Fours keeps talking like that. Didn't he criticize Ruthhilia for the same thing? Hypocrisy is such a sin. I bet that's what his sin is.
"Alright." I try to, uh, move from where I'm still trapped?
L approaches 56 and 57. "Ismalisa mentioned others who haven’t atoned yet. Chances are they’re the ones at the campfire."
"Being unsure of yourself is your greatest strength, John. It means you'll always be able to spot it before you go too far. Okay?"
"Anyways."
I try to tune back in to the other conversation.
"Hm. Why would they take so long? Are they stupid?" I think to myself. "Facing your past can't be that hard."

It's kind of fucking weird that Fours is so deadset on convincing the beastman that he's inherently a predator or whatever. I mean, he probably is, but something about the whole assumption just seems.. wrong?
I dunno. I don't care.

Do I really want to be unsure? This one says I should be, and the logic makes sense, but… it can’t be right. Can it? Because I don’t like being unsure. Honestly, if I gave it some time to settle, I think being unsure would hurt the most of anything I’ve felt so far. It’s painful. I don’t like it. But pain can be good in certain scenarios too, probably…
"I guess we should check out the other sinners." I snort. "Everyone here is a freak, haha..."
"Could be they got here less than 6 days ago. Or they’ve got an interesting story to tell. Could be both."
“…I’m going to the campfire. You can all have fun being racist or pissed at me.” I walk off in that direction.
“Oh, that sounds interesting!” I follow her.
"That does seem like the best idea, yeah. Warmth is important for our survival. Let's go, guys." I also plod along.
L follows.
I walk off and take Sixer with me.
I follow Jon.
Is Ruthilla following?
Hell yes.

They arrive at a village made up of 6 wooden houses with a larger one at the end. In the center of the village, next to the campfire, is a door covered in greenery labelled 'Birth'. It is tied shut with rope and nailed shut by wooden boards. 

There are 5 people walking around the village with various numbers on their prison outfits, all of which are lower than yours. #034 approaches all of you. "New arrivals?"
"Yes. Why is the door like that?"
"Oh!" I approach the door labeled birth. "Is this mine, since this is my sin?" I don't really know who I'm expecting to answer, haha.
I follow John to the birth door. "Hey, little guy... I promise, it isn't a sin to be alive. You're wonderful."
"That’s…" 34 grimaces, looking at the group. "We banned the doors. They’re dangerous."
I blush. "Th- thank you...!"
“Birth isn’t a sin. Apathy isn’t really, either? Not the set I’m familiar with. I guess there’s more than seven with these guys.” I scoff. “Dangerous?”
I walk up to the door, and try to see if there are any cracks on the bottom or sides that I can peer through. Maybe a keyhole?
"What do you mean dangerous? They're the only way to leave."
The door seems like it would be functional if all the stuff blocking it wasn't there.
"Wait, wait, guys. I have a question. How exactly do people *become* pregnant?"
I flinch visibly away from #34 upon seeing him, in a way that is distinctly obvious to everyone around me. I quickly move to.. uh... I don't know. Not look at him. Ever.
"Uhh... would probably have something to do with sex, if I had to say."

The utter strangeness of what the white lady is saying manages to distract me from my incredible inner turmoil at the sight of, uh, that. Um. Guy. I turn to her. "W-what's wrong with you?? Are you fuckin' five???"
"That seems sensible, John."
I give him a thumbs up.
“Mhm. It’s a consequence a woman faces for having sex with a man. …Consequence in a value-neutral sense, I suppose.”
I give Fours a thumbs up back.

I look at how Sixer flinches. Hm. I just stand next to her in case I can take advantage of this.

"S*x isn't real."
Something about John talking about sex does set me on edge, but I find it hard to articulate the specific reason why. It's probably nothing.
"Huh...Huh. It's coming to me, almost. Sex, huh? I'll have to think about the implications of this more. It's probably good, though!"
“We all have some form of memory loss. It’s feasible someone could forget what sex is, or if it exists.”

I bark out a laugh. "Gahaha... don't mince your words. It's toooootally consequential! In a bad sense." I sneer at the white woman. "Don't have sex, or you'll go to hell and die. Perverts everywhere..."
"Oh, really? Well, I hope I haven't had sex, then..."
I hope so too.

34 looks uncertain. "Think of it this way... We're all sinners, right? Criminals. Unlocking these memories would disturb the peace and return us to our criminal states. That's if we can even trust that the memories are real. If we did escape, would we really have anyone to go back to? I mean... Sinners and criminals probably accompany other sinners and criminals. There's nothing good for us outside of here. That's the chief's decree."

“None of us would exist without it. If you’re so hell-bent on denying the potential value of life, I don’t know why you’re still around.” That might be a little excessively harsh. “I think you shouldn’t kill yourself, though.”
I tilt my head at 34. "Wait, who's the chief?"
I flinch away from the killer guy. "W-what?? No one said anything about me killing myself..." I mumble, and do the 👉 👈 thing.
“Chief… so there’s an authority that’s blocked this off.” I smirk. “Makes sense. If it was really a unanimous agreement, physically blocking the door would be pointless.”
I try knocking on the door. Worth a shot.
"Can we talk to him?"
"The chief is #001. He got here first and he lives in the big hut. You can't go see him, though. I'm his liason with people." 34.
"Damn."
“Oh, I *can’t*, hm?” I walk over to 34 and look down on him. “Why not?”
The birth door? It does nothing in response.

I'm disappointed. An authority figure would have been a nice reference point in our mess of a social situation, even if he ended up being awful and stupid or something. Just, you know, seeing the full structure of it.

Ok, so Sixer killed herself. 

"Well, that's... dumb. We're supposed to atone. If we just stay here, that just means we stay here forever." Like I'd want to follow the orders of a chief. I'm much better than that.
34 takes out a sword. "You should probably have gone to fetch your things before you tried to intimidate me. He doesn't want to meet with anyone and that's that."
"S-stop trying to use intimidation to get through every social situation!" I bark at killer guy, before remembering who I'm talking to and the fact that he killed someone, which is scary.
Sword!!!! Ahhh!!!!

Ah, darn.

"Shouldn't the person with the largest number be in charge? I think that would make more sense, from my admittedly limited perspective."

“I don’t have any things to fetch. This is all there is, at the moment.” I gesture to myself. “You can try your luck, if you’d like. But I gained a bit of my memories already, and I can assure you I didn’t need a weapon to win.”
"Don't work your brain too hard, John."
"I, uh..." Hm.
I pat him on the shoulder.

"How many people are there on this island?" L.

"There were around 13 before you guys arrived. It fluctuates based on who arrives and who dies. No one's managed to leave yet, if that's what you're wondering. Though it might have gone down again, no one checks on the old man." 34.
I guess I can give my tail a little wag, as a treat.
I am still pondering the implications of the relationship between sex, pregnancy, and childbirth.
“People die? Of old age??” I squint.
"This Goddess sure is angry at a whole lot of people, huh?"
"I thought this was like, hell??? What do you mean people are dying???"
“Don’t dignify that title. If she’s an infallible goddess testing our atonement, why’s 62 dead under a pile of rubble? Doesn’t seem like that was a compelling test of his moral fiber!”
"I... I dunno, maybe the test was climbing out, because he was too lethargic in life."
"Wait, 63. Do you not remember that death exists?"

"This place seems roughly equivalent to a prison, right? Doesn't the death penalty exist? Just because none of us have done things bad enough to recieve it doesn't mean that it can't apply to other people."
"Death and sex are pretty similar, right? It's pretty fair not to remember either..."

"There are animals around. Sometimes they get a little taste for human flesh when a hunter gets sloppy. Plus... Well, we don't actually know what happens to most of them. Sometimes some of them just turn up chopped to pieces. It only happens once every few months though. We're fine most of the time." 34.

"Every few *months?*" L.
“I’m well aware death exists. I’m just trying to gather how this place works, because it’s clearly not something you can parse intuitively.”
"Well, I think it's a bit like a prison."
"W-what the fffuck???" I stammer, terrified. This is hell... this is hell... and he's here too.. this must be hell...
"Animals...?"
"Like... You. They don't usually talk, though." 34.
"A month is a long time. I'd imagine months is even longer."
"I wouldn't be too worried."
“Months is like a month, but more than one. It could be two, or even more.”
"Gosh, why would they... would they really just attack someone out of the blue? I suppose they're only attacking hunters... self defense is alright... comparatively..."
"We don't even know how many days there are."
I sniffle.

"The length is exactly the problem. How long have you all been in Sinspace?" L.

"...I've been here a little over a year. The chief and his original allies got here 3 years ago." 34.

Wow, getting him mad was quick. It's fine, I can work this out.  I'm very good at this.
